These look like great places to use a for comprehension to avoid all this nested mapping. In particular your last `match` here doesn't really do anything...seems like you could just make the call to `environmentRevisionRetriever.retrieve` and log if it is empty. I would try something like
```
val environmentRevision = for {
  envRevKey <- run.trigger.environmentRevisionKey
  envRevId <- envRevKey.environmentRevisionId
} yield {
  environmentRevisionRetriever.retrieve(envRevId)
}
if (environmentRevision.isEmpty) {
  logger.debug(s"Could not get environment revision for run ${run.id} to get image size")
}
```
You can probably do something similar for `containerNameToImageSizeMap` or extend the for comprehension I defined to extract the image size

Oh that's nice, TIL. Looks something like this now, which is much cleaner I think.
```scala
val containerNameToImageSizeMap = for {
  environmentRevisionKey <- run.trigger.environmentRevisionKey
  environmentRevisionId = environmentRevisionKey.environmentRevisionId
  environmentRevision = environmentRevisionRetriever.retrieve(environmentRevisionId)
  compressedImageSize <- environmentRevision.metadata.compressedImageSize
} yield {
  Map("run" -> compressedImageSize)
}
```

Changed to look like
```scala
val images: List[Image] = imageCounts.map {
  case (imageName, count) => (for {
    containerName <- imageNameToContainerNameMap.get(imageName)
    sizeBytes = containerNameToImageSizeBytesMap.get(containerName)
  } yield {
    Image(
      name = imageName,
      numContainers = count,
      sizeBytes = sizeBytes
    )
  }).get
}.toList
```
Also removed the explanatory comment, since it feels more readable when written like this.
